value.0: "Right. Your name is on the guild registry. Is there anything else?"
"You will be allowed to trade in any pelts you recover during your expeditions. Just tell me you have something to trade and I'll give you a deal."
"You also get a discount from me. I should think you could make your money back in no time."
This dwarf fidgets and plays with her swords as she hums an off-tune little song to herself. As you approach she sighs and taps her foot impatiently.
"You look like the kind of soul who has spent a great deal of time in the wilds, so be welcomed here to the Quartermaster's Store."
"You look like the kind of soul who has spent a great deal of time in the wilds, so be welcomed here to the Quartermaster's Store."
"You must be the new one running for Lord of the Keep. As master of the foresters' guild, I've heard a few things about you. Are you here for supplies or about the election?"
"Right. Don't go getting yourself killed."
"Why do you always say that?"
"Well, some people need practical advice."
"Very good. I do a lot of business so my stock changes quite rapidly. I hope I have something of interest to you."
"Since you are a member of our guild, I will give you better prices."
"Right. Go ahead."
"Right. I suppose you think all we do here is sit around waiting for folks to walk in and ask us questions."
"You mean we don't?"
"And here I thought that's what you were paying us for, Floater!"
"What kind of questions would you like me to answer, <FirstName>?"
"I can answer questions or sell you some equipment, but I prefer the latter."
"What kind of information?"
"There's two edges on that blade, there is. On the one hand, there's the forces he brought with him. On the other, the monsters have been building up their numbers hereabouts for a long time now."
"It's like they've been building up, waiting for the Masked Man to lead them. We warned the keep several years ago and that's when the Banner started to rebuild the army."
"The Mossy Tree has a much better atmosphere."
"Right here. No better shop in town, according to me."
"You could hunt a manticore."

"The foresters' guild was created to protect the interests of the woodsmen and the hunters. We make up a large portion of the revenue for the keep, exporting furs and other products to the southern cities."

"The largest problem is that we get very little respect. The only other guild master who treats us well is Serah, of the landowners' guild. She knows what goes on outside the keep, so she understands."
"You don't have to be rude about it."
"She understands that sometimes a loner needs to come into town and let loose a little. Go a little crazy."
"What else would you like to know?"
"As a ranger, I will make you a member of the guild, for 100 gold."
"That is too bad. I'm sure you'll be able to come up with the gold somehow. It's really worth it."

Comment.value: if PC is female and Romance is on.

value.0: "Ha! A fine woman you are, but I have interests elsewhere..."
"We shall see. We shall see."
"I try not to think about it. Personally, I don't really care for either of the other candidates. Enivid doesn't like us, and Sir Becket thinks he's better than us."
"If I had to choose right now, I'd probably vote for Becket, since I don't know anything about you."
"Anyone could stand here and tell me exactly what they think I want to hear. I don't stand by words very much."
"Now, if you could prove that you understand the mind of a hunter... that would tell me something."
"That is an argument we can have at a later time. What I want is no helpless animal."
"Any fool with a weapon can kill something, what I want is something more specific."

"Before I became the guildmaster, I was preparing to stalk a manticore that's been lingering in the ruins of the old wizards' school in the Emerald Hills. The wizards would harvest them for their hides, 'cause they're said to be easy to enchant."

"They had some trap involving crystals and water barrels and poison gas and luring the manticore into an enclosed space - you know wizards, they always make things more complicated than they need to be. Anyhow, I'm guessing everything should still be in place."
"The skin of a manticore has powerful magic in it. Sometimes when you kill a manticore the normal way, the skin is too badly damaged to be useful."

"The wizards' trap will impair the beast in such a way that you should be able to kill it without destroying the skin. Kill the manticore and you'll have my vote. Bring it intact and I'll make it into a magic cloak for you."
"I would prefer to leave it up to you to figure it out. That is, after all, the test to see if you can think like a hunter. All I will say is that you will need at least two poison crystals."

"Now I should tell you that the wizards' ruins are filled with all manner of strange things and smaller monsters that feed off the remains of the manticore's kills. It should be an interesting hunt. Now are you interested?"

value.0: "Sweetest woman in the world, and a great cuddle... if you like a knife in your guts. Har, har!"
"Now that's the kind of dross that gets us in trouble. I figured with people like the Hand and the Banner running the keep, we needed someone to protect our interests."
"They don't like us folk, since most of us are 'chaotic' in nature, according to the law makers. Just because we don't act all civilized and that nonsense."
"We like our drink strong and our bar fights brutal. That doesn't sit well with someone like the Hand."
"That what we like to hear. Someone who can identify with us, unlike most of the locals."
"You hear that boys and girls? 'Our type' seek out trouble!"
"Maybe 'our type' ought to seek a little trouble right now!"
"Yes, some butt-kicking for goodness!"
"Now boys, calm yourselves. There's no need to make matters worse. I'm sure <FirstName> didn't mean anything by it."
"Well, <mister/missus>, this is one guild that won't be voting for you... or selling you supplies. Now get lost."
"Oh, sorry. Just tired of the locals and their attitudes."
"Townsfolk don't mind us spending our gold here though, which is why I bought this shop when I became guildmaster. Might as well keep the gold in the family, so to speak."
"But enough about us, what else would you like to know? Or are you ready to spend a little gold on some supplies?"
"The impurities that float on top of molten metal that smiths can't stand. That’s what we are to a lot of the townsfolk."
"Because I could move so quietly that it seemed like I was floating above the ground. No mean feat for a dwarf out of the mountains."
"I loved hunting ferocious beasts. Had to give it up though, to be the guildmaster."
